    "view": {
      "representation": "view",
      "value": "<p>Using <a href=\"/wiki/spaces/REN26/pages/19661911/PxrCryptomatte\" data-linked-resource-id=\"19661911\" data-linked-resource-version=\"2\" data-linked-resource-type=\"page\">PxrCryptomatte</a> workflow, you can output IDs in Maya for easy selection in a compositing application. You can then use that selection as a mask to make changes selectively in post packages.</p><p>PxrCryptomatte is supplied as a <a href=\"/wiki/spaces/REN26/pages/19661887/Sample+and+Display+Filters\" data-linked-resource-id=\"19661887\" data-linked-resource-version=\"2\" data-linked-resource-type=\"page\">Sample Filter</a> plugin. As such the output for Cryptomatte is stored as a separate EXR file from your beauty or denoise outputs. Please note an OpenEXR is required to store the values correctly.</p><span class=\"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper image-center-wrapper\"><img class=\"confluence-embedded-image image-center\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://renderman.atlassian.net/wiki/download/attachments/544543618/rfmMakeCryptomatte.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1754431599419&amp;cacheVersion=1&amp;api=v2\" data-image-src=\"https://renderman.atlassian.net/wiki/download/attachments/544543618/rfmMakeCryptomatte.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1754431599419&amp;cacheVersion=1&amp;api=v2\" data-height=\"608\" data-width=\"478\" data-unresolved-comment-count=\"0\" data-linked-resource-id=\"544543640\" data-linked-resource-version=\"1\" data-linked-resource-type=\"attachment\" data-linked-resource-default-alias=\"rfmMakeCryptomatte.png\" data-base-url=\"https://renderman.atlassian.net/wiki\" data-linked-resource-content-type=\"image/png\" data-linked-resource-container-id=\"544543618\" data-linked-resource-container-version=\"1\" data-media-id=\"2a809594-adb0-4960-b007-c0b823203bc1\" data-media-type=\"file\"></span><p>Under the <strong>Features Tab</strong> of the <strong>Render Settings</strong>, navigate to the <strong>Images / Sample Filters</strong> tab and right click on an empty slot to select <strong>create a PxrCryptomatte</strong>.</p><span class=\"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper image-center-wrapper\"><img class=\"confluence-embedded-image image-center\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://renderman.atlassian.net/wiki/download/attachments/544543618/rfmMakeCryptomatteOptions.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1754431599419&amp;cacheVersion=1&amp;api=v2\" data-image-src=\"https://renderman.atlassian.net/wiki/download/attachments/544543618/rfmMakeCryptomatteOptions.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1754431599419&amp;cacheVersion=1&amp;api=v2\" data-height=\"435\" data-width=\"477\" data-unresolved-comment-count=\"0\" data-linked-resource-id=\"544543637\" data-linked-resource-version=\"1\" data-linked-resource-type=\"attachment\" data-linked-resource-default-alias=\"rfmMakeCryptomatteOptions.png\" data-base-url=\"https://renderman.atlassian.net/wiki\" data-linked-resource-content-type=\"image/png\" data-linked-resource-container-id=\"544543618\" data-linked-resource-container-version=\"1\" data-media-id=\"736b62cc-e68e-40ef-a6d5-5ef090d97f91\" data-media-type=\"file\"></span><p>The options above are default. You can find out more about the options by visiting the <a href=\"/wiki/spaces/REN26/pages/19661911/PxrCryptomatte\" data-linked-resource-id=\"19661911\" data-linked-resource-version=\"2\" data-linked-resource-type=\"page\">PxrCryptomatte</a> page.</p><p>Note that after you create a Sample Filter, another empty connection will be created, allowing you to output Cryptomatte files using different criteria. For example, if you wanted one for per-object and another per-material, create another PxrCryptomatte for output and specify another name for the file.</p><p>For now, a separate OpenEXR is required to be output for each plugin, separate from your denoise or beauty EXRs. You can create a sequence by using the correct token, example: cryptomatte.&lt;f4&gt;.exr creates a rendered sequence with a padding of 4 spaces, cryptomatte.0001.exr</p><p>Below is an example in Nuke using our Robot Room Community Scene.</p><span class=\"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper image-center-wrapper\"><img class=\"confluence-embedded-image image-center\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://renderman.atlassian.net/wiki/download/attachments/544543618/nuke-select-1.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1754431599419&amp;cacheVersion=1&amp;api=v2\" data-image-src=\"https://renderman.atlassian.net/wiki/download/attachments/544543618/nuke-select-1.png?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1754431599419&amp;cacheVersion=1&amp;api=v2\" data-height=\"1060\" data-width=\"1180\" data-unresolved-comment-count=\"0\" data-linked-resource-id=\"544543634\" data-linked-resource-version=\"1\" data-linked-resource-type=\"attachment\" data-linked-resource-default-alias=\"nuke-select-1.png\" data-base-url=\"https://renderman.atlassian.net/wiki\" data-linked-resource-content-type=\"image/png\" data-linked-resource-container-id=\"544543618\" data-linked-resource-container-version=\"1\" data-media-id=\"c04d7b68-d014-4319-a7ba-a0215e64e4cc\" data-media-type=\"file\"></span><p><br/></p><p>You can set a user string attribute in multiple ways if you want to assign an ID to geometry. Examples are as follows:</p><p>You could use a pre-assigned LPE group if you wanted those to match</p><p>Tell Cryptomatte you want to use: identifier:lpegroup</p><p>When choosing identifier:name it will return the instance (transform)</p><p>When choosing identifier:object it will return the leaf level shape node.</p><p> <br/></p><p><br/></p>"
    }
  },
